---
import CaseLayout from '../layouts/CaseLayout.astro';
import ReaderColumn from '../components/reader/ReaderColumn.astro';
import Hero from '../components/reader/Hero.astro';
import MetaRow from '../components/reader/MetaRow.astro';
import Section from '../components/reader/Section.astro';
import SectionLabel from '../components/reader/SectionLabel.astro';
import H2 from '../components/reader/H2.astro';
import Lead from '../components/reader/Lead.astro';
import Body from '../components/reader/Body.astro';
import Callout from '../components/reader/Callout.astro';
import PullQuote from '../components/reader/PullQuote.astro';
import MarginRef from '../components/reader/MarginRef.astro';
import Hr from '../components/reader/Hr.astro';
import Outcome from '../components/reader/Outcome.astro';
import EndRow from '../components/reader/EndRow.astro';
import ImgSlot from '../components/reader/ImgSlot.astro';
---

<CaseLayout
  title="Asset Management — Sivanesh TV"
  caseNum="03"
  caseName="Asset Management"
  description="Designing Asset Management for FlytBase — an infrastructure-first module for tracking drones, payloads, and ground equipment across every site."
  ogImage="/assets/asset/asset-hero.png"
  jsonLd={{
    '@context': 'https://schema.org',
    '@type': 'CreativeWork',
    name: 'Asset Management',
    description: 'Designing Asset Management for FlytBase — an infrastructure-first module for tracking drones, payloads, and ground equipment across every site.',
    url: 'https://sivanesh.tv/asset',
    author: { '@type': 'Person', name: 'Sivanesh TV', url: 'https://sivanesh.tv' },
    keywords: 'product design, asset management, infrastructure, inspection systems',
  }}
>
  <Fragment slot="reader">
    <ReaderColumn>
      <Hero
        eyebrow="case study · 03"
        title='Asset <em>Management.</em>'
        sub="Designing FlytBase's first product that isn't about the flight."
      />

      <MetaRow items={[
        { k: 'Role', v: 'Lead Product designer' },
        { k: 'Year', v: '2025' },
        { k: 'Scope', v: 'End-to-end UX · Prototype' },
        { k: 'Tools', v: 'Figma · Claude · Lovable' },
      ]} />

      <ImgSlot variant="hero"
        src="/assets/asset/asset-hero.png"
        alt="Asset Management dashboard — left nav rail, asset tree grouped by sector, map with zone annotations and asset pins"
        cap="Asset Management · the main view"
        capMeta="the interface"
      />

      <!-- § 01 Context -->
      <Section>
        <SectionLabel text="Context" num="§ 01" />
        <H2>FlytBase had always been <em>flight-first.</em> This module wasn't.</H2>
        <Lead>Cockpit, Fleet, Mission Planning, Scheduler — every surface FlytBase had shipped until now was about the flight. The path the drone takes. The waypoints. The commands. Asset Management was the first time we were building a product that <em>doesn't care about the flight.</em></Lead>
        <Body>
          <p>Sarah Martinez runs operations at Devon Energy. She's responsible for 45+ wellheads spread across 15 square miles in North Cowden Unit. She schedules inspections, coordinates with maintenance teams, and files monthly compliance reports to regulators. She uses drones because they're faster and safer than sending people, but drones aren't her job. <em>The wellheads</em> are her job.</p>
          <p>On the existing FlytBase dashboard, she could fly missions. What she couldn't do was answer the question her boss asked her every week: <em>"when was wellhead NC-0217 last inspected?"</em> The answer existed, somewhere, in a mission log she'd have to find by name. The software she used every day didn't know what a wellhead was.</p>
        </Body>
      </Section>

      <!-- § 02 The problem -->
      <Section>
        <SectionLabel text="The problem" num="§ 02" />
        <PullQuote>You could fly missions. You couldn't manage <em>things.</em></PullQuote>
        <Body>
          <p>The existing system recorded flights beautifully — every waypoint, every telemetry reading, every piece of captured media. But infrastructure only existed as a string inside a mission's name. "Wellhead NC-0217 - Monthly Inspection" was the only thread tying a place to a flight, and that thread broke the moment someone mistyped the name, changed the naming convention, or inspected the same asset under a different mission.</p>
          <p>There was no list of Sarah's wellheads anywhere in the product. No inspection history per asset. No way to see how a wellhead's condition had changed over six months. No templates for "here's how you always inspect this type of thing." Every monthly report Sarah filed, she built from scratch by scavenging across dozens of mission logs.</p>
        </Body>
        <Callout><p>The gap wasn't missing features. It was a missing <em>abstraction.</em> The software didn't have a concept for the thing the user actually cared about.</p></Callout>
      </Section>

      <Hr />

      <!-- § 03 The shift -->
      <Section>
        <SectionLabel text="The shift" num="§ 03" />
        <H2>Track the thing. <em>Not the flight.</em></H2>
        <Lead>This sounds small. It wasn't. Every product surface FlytBase had shipped was flight-first — and this new module had to sit alongside them, in the same authentication, the same navigation, the same customer account, but operate on a <em>completely different axis.</em></Lead>
        <Body>
          <p>The natural-seeming move was to embed asset functionality inside Operations — same dashboard, new tab, assets as a property of the existing system. We almost went there. What stopped us was recognising that asset management isn't drone operations at a different scale — it's a different <em>kind</em> of work, on a different <em>time horizon</em>. Operations lives in minutes and hours; asset management lives in months, audit cycles, and regulatory trails. One surface couldn't serve both without compromising both.</p>
          <p>So we built it as a separate product — launched from the FlytBase hamburger menu, with its own data model centred on <strong>Assets</strong>. An asset is a record — a wellhead, a power line, a pipeline, a generator — with its own ID, its own inspection history, its own media library, its own alert thresholds. Flights don't disappear. They stop being the centre of the universe.</p>
          <p>The Operations Dashboard continues to fly drones, but increasingly <em>everything you do there now references an asset.</em> You launch GoToAsset instead of GoToLocation. The Cockpit's launcher panel has a slot reserved for asset-dispatch flows — not shipped yet, but the architecture is ready. The flight becomes a means. The asset is the end.</p>
        </Body>
        <MarginRef jump="shift-principle">↗ see the shift principle</MarginRef>

        <ImgSlot variant="wide"
          src="/assets/asset/asset-detail-generator.png"
          alt="Asset Detail page — Industrial Generator Unit showing category, status, inspection history, reference images and map location"
          cap="Asset details · Overview"
        />

        <ImgSlot variant="wide"
          src="/assets/asset/asset-image-collab.png"
          alt="Asset media viewer with image annotation and collaboration — comments threaded to inspection captures"
          cap="Asset Detail · image viewer and collaboration"
          capMeta="media in context"
        />

        <ImgSlot variant="wide"
          src="/assets/asset/asset-compare.png"
          alt="Asset compare view — two inspection captures from different dates side by side showing change over time"
          cap="Asset Detail · inspection comparison"
          capMeta="change over time"
        />
      </Section>

      <!-- § 04 Templatization -->
      <Section>
        <SectionLabel text="The payoff" num="§ 04" />
        <H2>Once assets exist, <em>templates become possible.</em></H2>
        <Lead>This is the operational unlock. Without an asset abstraction, every inspection is configured from scratch. With assets in the data model, configuration moves up one level: define the inspection once, apply it to every instance of that type. <em>Setup time stops scaling with fleet size.</em></Lead>
        <Body>
          <p><strong>Inspection Profiles</strong> are reusable viewpoint definitions. Two types: <em>Grid</em> for area coverage (area, GSD, overlap), <em>Viewpoints</em> for discrete points (waypoints, lens, zoom, gimbal attitude). One profile per asset type, reused across every instance of that type.</p>
          <p>The same logic applies to <strong>Alert Profiles</strong>. A wellhead has different abnormal-temperature thresholds than a substation, which has different thresholds than a pipeline. Each asset type gets its own alert library. The software learns the rules once. The operator never re-teaches it.</p>
        </Body>

        <ImgSlot variant="wide"
          src="/assets/asset/asset-inspection-profiles.png"
          alt="Inspection Profiles tab — named viewpoint profile cards showing drone model, camera, distance and viewpoint count with asset map"
          cap="Inspection profiles"
        />

        <ImgSlot variant="wide"
          src="/assets/asset/asset-profile-creation.png"
          alt="Inspection profile creation flow — grid and viewpoint type selection with drone, camera and coverage parameter configuration"
          cap="Profile creation"
        />
      </Section>

      <!-- § 05 The five pages -->
      <Section>
        <SectionLabel text="The module" num="§ 05" />
        <H2>Five pages. <em>One coherent model.</em></H2>
        <Lead>The navigation isn't decoration — it's the data schema, made visible. Each page is the same asset data, sliced a different way. If you understand the navigation, you understand the data model.</Lead>
        <Body>
          <p><strong>Assets</strong> — the canonical record. Import 1000+ via KML or CSV, organise by site or sector, search and filter. The map reflects the active selection.</p>
          <p><strong>Inspection Logs</strong> — sliced by flight. Every inspection that happened anywhere, searchable, with media and map context one click away.</p>
          <p><strong>Media</strong> — sliced by captured imagery. Every photo, every video, chronologically, tagged, annotated. The surface for evidence review.</p>
          <p><strong>Reports</strong> — sliced by stakeholder. Compliance, maintenance, custom — generated from asset records, distributed as PDF, secure link, or QR.</p>
          <p><strong>Tag Management</strong> — sliced by classification. Tags are records, not strings. Create, merge, rename, retire. When you have 1000+ assets, tag sprawl is an operational problem the schema has to handle.</p>
        </Body>

        <ImgSlot variant="wide"
          src="/assets/asset/asset-page.png"
          alt="Assets page — the canonical record. Left nav rail, asset tree with sector grouping, map with annotated zones and asset pins"
          cap="Assets · the canonical record and module home"
          capMeta="1 of 5"
        />

        <ImgSlot variant="wide"
          src="/assets/asset/asset-inspection-logs.png"
          alt="Inspection Logs page — every inspection searchable with media and map context"
          cap="Inspection Logs · every inspection, searchable"
          capMeta="2 of 5 · sliced by flight"
        />

        <ImgSlot variant="wide"
          src="/assets/asset/asset-media.png"
          alt="Media page — all captured images and video chronologically tagged and annotated"
          cap="Media · every capture, tagged and annotated"
          capMeta="3 of 5 · sliced by image"
        />

        <ImgSlot variant="wide"
          src="/assets/asset/asset-reports.png"
          alt="Reports page — compliance, maintenance and custom reports generated from asset records"
          cap="Reports · compliance, maintenance, custom"
          capMeta="4 of 5 · sliced by stakeholder"
        />

        <ImgSlot variant="wide"
          src="/assets/asset/asset-tags.png"
          alt="Tag Management page — tags as records, create merge rename retire with 1000+ assets"
          cap="Tag Management · tags as records, not strings"
          capMeta="5 of 5 · sliced by classification"
        />
      </Section>

      <!-- § 06 Outcome -->
      <Section>
        <SectionLabel text="What shipped" num="§ 06" />
        <H2>M1 went live as a <em>second product.</em></H2>
        <Lead>Asset Management shipped as a standalone dashboard inside the FlytBase ecosystem — same authentication, same customer account, separate surface. It's the first FlytBase module that isn't about flying a drone.</Lead>

        <Outcome items={[
          { n: '1000+', l: 'Assets at import', d: 'KML and CSV import handles the scale Devon Energy and enterprise customers actually have.' },
          { n: 'M1', l: 'Shipped', d: 'All five pages live with asset detail, inspection profiles, media gallery, and reports distribution.' },
          { n: '2nd', l: 'Product', d: 'FlytBase is no longer a single-product company. Asset Management is the second, and the foundation for more.' },
        ]} />
      </Section>

      <!-- § 07 Reflection -->
      <Section>
        <SectionLabel text="What I learnt" num="§ 07" />
        <Body>
          <p><strong>Sometimes the problem isn't a feature. It's an abstraction.</strong> No number of improvements to mission logs would have solved Sarah's problem, because her problem was that the software didn't have a concept for the thing she cared about. Finding the right abstraction was the work. Everything downstream followed from it.</p>
          <p><strong>Shifts like this compound.</strong> Once assets exist, templates become possible. Once templates exist, setup time collapses. Once data is structured by asset, reports become queries. Once Operations references assets, GoToAsset replaces GoToLocation. Each downstream win was free — we got it by making one decision correctly early.</p>
          <p><strong>A product company can enter new categories from a strong base.</strong> Asset Management isn't a pivot. It's a second product that sits next to the first, serves the same customers, and expands what FlytBase is. That's a different kind of work — less refinement, more invention — and it's the kind I want to keep doing.</p>
        </Body>
      </Section>

      <EndRow note="— end of case · § 03 / 03 —" nextLabel="Back to the workbench ↗" nextHref="/" />
    </ReaderColumn>
  </Fragment>

  <Fragment slot="artifacts">
    <!-- §01 CONTEXT — wayfinding -->
    <div class="marker md red artifact" data-anchor="0" data-anchor-offset="-80" data-side="left" data-gap="60" data-width="200" style="position:absolute;transform:rotate(-8deg);font-family:var(--fh);font-weight:700;font-size:34px;line-height:1.1;color:var(--marker-red)">↓ read straight through</div>
    <div class="marker sm black artifact" data-anchor="0" data-anchor-offset="-40" data-side="right" data-gap="40" data-width="180" style="position:absolute;transform:rotate(4deg);font-family:var(--fh);font-weight:700;font-size:18px;line-height:1.1;color:var(--ink)">drag around to<br>explore →</div>

    <!-- §01 CONTEXT — operational scale framed as a quiet context card -->
    <div class="context-card artifact" id="obj-scale-context" data-anchor="0" data-anchor-offset="380" data-side="left" data-gap="60" data-width="380" style="position:absolute;transform:rotate(-2deg);width:380px;padding:28px;background:#1a1a1c;color:#f5ede0;box-shadow:3px 5px 0 rgba(40,35,25,.1),6px 14px 28px rgba(40,35,25,.25)">
      <div style="position:absolute;top:-10px;left:12%;width:80px;height:20px;background:var(--tape);opacity:.85;transform:rotate(-3deg)"></div>
      <div style="font-family:var(--fm);font-size:9px;font-weight:500;letter-spacing:.2em;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--red);margin-bottom:14px">— the operational reality —</div>
      <div style="font-family:var(--fs);font-weight:600;font-size:19px;line-height:1.3;color:#fdf8ea;margin-bottom:12px">45 wellheads. 15 square miles. <em style="font-style:italic;color:var(--red)">One</em> Operations Manager.</div>
      <div style="font-family:var(--fs);font-size:12px;line-height:1.6;color:rgba(253,248,234,.75)">She's responsible for the inspections, the compliance reports, the maintenance coordination. She uses FlytBase every day — but the wellheads are her job, not the drones.</div>
    </div>

    <!-- §02 PROBLEM — Sarah's actual question -->
    <div class="sticky pink artifact" id="obj-sarah-quote" data-anchor="1" data-anchor-offset="40" data-side="left" data-gap="60" data-width="300" style="position:absolute;transform:rotate(-4deg);width:300px;min-height:180px;padding:22px 20px 18px;font-family:var(--fh);font-weight:500;font-size:20px;line-height:1.35;color:var(--ink);background:#ff8fa3;box-shadow:2px 4px 0 rgba(40,35,25,.05),4px 8px 16px rgba(40,35,25,.18)">
      <div class="sticky-eyebrow" style="font-family:var(--fm);font-size:9px;font-weight:500;letter-spacing:.14em;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--ink-3);margin-bottom:8px">— the question that doesn't have an answer —</div>
      <em style="font-style:normal;color:var(--red);font-weight:700">"When was wellhead NC-0217 last inspected?"</em><br><br>She gets asked this every week. She spends thirty minutes every week finding out.
    </div>

    <!-- §02 — the missing abstraction pattern -->
    <div class="sticky artifact" id="obj-missing-abstraction" data-anchor="1" data-anchor-offset="380" data-side="left" data-gap="60" data-width="280" style="position:absolute;transform:rotate(3deg);width:280px;min-height:180px;padding:22px 20px 18px;font-family:var(--fh);font-weight:500;font-size:20px;line-height:1.35;color:var(--ink);background:var(--yellow);box-shadow:2px 4px 0 rgba(40,35,25,.05),4px 8px 16px rgba(40,35,25,.18)">
      <div class="sticky-eyebrow" style="font-family:var(--fm);font-size:9px;font-weight:500;letter-spacing:.14em;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--ink-3);margin-bottom:8px">— the diagnosis —</div>
      Infrastructure existed as a <em style="font-style:normal;color:var(--red);font-weight:700">string</em> inside a mission's name. Nothing more. The software didn't know what a wellhead <em style="font-style:normal;color:var(--red);font-weight:700">was.</em>
    </div>

    <!-- §03 THE SHIFT — THE PRINCIPLE CARD -->
    <div class="principle artifact" id="obj-shift-principle" data-anchor="2" data-anchor-offset="20" data-side="right" data-gap="80" data-width="400" style="position:absolute;transform:rotate(1.5deg);width:400px;padding:32px 32px 28px;background:var(--paper);box-shadow:3px 5px 0 rgba(40,35,25,.06),6px 14px 28px rgba(40,35,25,.2);border:1px solid rgba(40,35,25,.08)">
      <div style="position:absolute;top:-12px;right:10%;width:90px;height:22px;background:var(--tape);opacity:.85;transform:rotate(3deg);box-shadow:0 2px 6px rgba(40,35,25,.1)"></div>
      <div style="font-family:var(--fm);font-size:9px;font-weight:500;letter-spacing:.2em;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--red);margin-bottom:14px;display:flex;align-items:center;gap:8px"><span>◆</span>the shift that created a second product</div>
      <div style="font-family:var(--fs);font-weight:700;font-size:26px;line-height:1.15;letter-spacing:-.02em;color:var(--ink);margin-bottom:10px">Everything else FlytBase had built was about the flight. <em style="font-style:italic;color:var(--red)">This one was about the asset.</em></div>
      <div style="font-family:var(--fs);font-size:13px;line-height:1.55;color:var(--ink-2);margin-bottom:14px">Cockpit, Fleet, Mission Planning — all flight-first. Asset Management was the first module that doesn't care about the path the drone takes. It cares about the <em style="font-style:italic;color:var(--ink)">thing the drone was sent to look at.</em></div>
      <div style="font-family:var(--fh);font-weight:600;font-size:17px;color:var(--ink-3);padding-top:12px;border-top:1px dashed rgba(40,35,25,.18)">— the abstraction that unlocks the module</div>
    </div>

    <!-- §03 — the shift diagram: flight-first vs asset-first mental model -->
    <div class="diagram artifact" id="obj-shift-diagram" data-anchor="2" data-anchor-offset="560" data-side="right" data-gap="60" data-width="460" style="position:absolute;width:460px;transform:rotate(-1deg);padding:24px;background:var(--paper);box-shadow:2px 3px 0 rgba(40,35,25,.04),4px 8px 20px rgba(40,35,25,.18)">
      <div style="position:absolute;top:-10px;left:40%;width:60px;height:20px;background:var(--tape);opacity:.85;transform:rotate(-3deg)"></div>
      <div style="font-family:var(--fh);font-weight:700;font-size:22px;color:var(--ink);margin-bottom:4px">The mental-model shift</div>
      <div style="font-family:var(--fm);font-size:9px;letter-spacing:.14em;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--ink-3);margin-bottom:16px">— what sits at the centre —</div>
      <svg viewBox="0 0 420 260" width="100%">
        <!-- Before: flight-first -->
        <g transform="translate(10 20)">
          <text x="90" y="0" text-anchor="middle" font-family="JetBrains Mono" font-size="9" fill="#7a7770" letter-spacing="1">BEFORE — FLIGHT-FIRST</text>
          <rect x="63" y="37" width="54" height="26" rx="3" style="fill:var(--ink)"/>
          <text x="90" y="54" text-anchor="middle" font-family="Inter" font-size="10" style="fill:var(--paper)" font-weight="700">FLIGHT</text>
